architecturalDecisions.subjectArea: Using Cloud Pack For Integration Along With OpenShift Container Platform vs App Connect SaaS Offering
architecturalDecisions.name: App Connect Deployment Strategy
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement:
As currently designed, using ACE SaaS offering on IBM cloud; we’ve experienced the following issues:
• Lack of monitoring for container’s consumption (CPU/Memory)
• Automated deployment is not supported in ACE SaaS offering, only manual deployments through the dashboard
• Occurrence of multiple unplanned outage incidents with ACE SaaS
• There are no supported management APIs to manage the running servers and perform health checks
• Container logs are not meeting technical requirements for logging necessary business data in order to support in troubleshooting integration flows
architecturalDecisions.motivation:
• Considering the aggressive workload and expected throughput for Brexit, the current ACE SaaS architecture wouldn’t support HA and auto-scalability
• More reliable deployments with Red Hat OpenShift and utilization of docker and container orchestration capabilities
• Automated deployments for integration flows and eliminate the risk caused by manual interference

alternatives.name: ACE SaaS Offering with HA Implementation
alternatives.description: ACE SaaS offering with HA implementation, which can be achieved by provisioning multiple instances in different geographical regions while considering an increase in the integration servers’ replicas

alternatives.name: Using CP4I Along With OpenShift Container Platform
alternatives.description:
Deployment strategy to be as follows:

Deployment of the integration flows over three different zones, In each zone, there are multiple integration server pods running ACE flows and processing the client requests with the implemented integration logic as in the figure below





• For HA implementation, the workload is completely balanced between two clusters deployed on two different regions. A global load balancer is configured to transfer the request between both regions. Both clusters are in completely different location geographically and in a different network. There is no internal network communication among them as in the below figure

architecturalDecisions.decision: Using CP4I Along With OpenShift Container Platform
architecturalDecisions.justification:
• Fine-grained deployment and pipeline automated deployments are supported through OpenShift container platform
• IBM Cloud Paks for integration provides logging service (based on the ELK stack) and monitoring service (based on Prometheus and Grafana)
• Monitoring for integration servers’ consumption would alert if any expected failures and action can be taken to increase scalability
architecturalDecisions.implications:
• Increase agility and productivity
    • Fully support the agile integration architecture concepts.
    • Dynamic scalability and inherit resilience
    • Management and maintainability provided with OpenShift CP4I
architecturalDecisions.relatedDecisions:
• RH OpenShift container platform to deploy cloud pack for integration
    • Non-production environment to only have different entitlement and HA won’t be supported for cost saving

architecturalDecisions.subjectArea: Provision a dedicated Cloudant instance for App Connect usage
architecturalDecisions.name: App Connect Data Layer Addition (Cloudant + COS)
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement:
Either using a dedicated or shared Cloudant instance for App Connect

• Read/Write operations and global queries' quota limitation for the shared database instance between backend and App Connect
• Delays resulted from waiting for R/W operations might impact App connect performance
• A shared database would be a single point of failure for both integration and the core layer in case of outage
architecturalDecisions.motivation:
• Solidify the integration data layer with a tenant-isolated database
• Increase overall security as the App Connect layer is controlled by tenant
• Support different availability requirements and simplify administration and backup for different backup schedules and recovery models

alternatives.name: Backend and App Connect to use the same Cloudant database instance
alternatives.description: Backend and App Connect to use the same Cloudant database instance

alternatives.name: Use Dedicated Cloudant Instance
alternatives.description: Use Dedicated Cloudant Instance

architecturalDecisions.implications:
• Enhancing the performance 
    • Solidifying and securing the integration data layer
    • Giving the tenant all the rights needed to control/manage App Connect database
architecturalDecisions.derivedRequirements: DevOps requirements for the backup and recovery of the new database instance

architecturalDecisions.subjectArea: Event streaming vs. Messaging for App connect logger
architecturalDecisions.name: App Connect Kafka vs. MQ Support For Logging Optimization (Kafka Standard) - Compare With MQ In The Cloud Pak
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement:
• The current logging service (LogDNA) truncates large payload, so a customized logger application is developed to store payloads in cloud object storage while using LogDNA Ingest API to log COS URLs
• LogDNA Ingest API is having a performance impact on application performance because of the consumed time for logging
architecturalDecisions.assumptions: Usage of common services for logging and monitoring provided by IBM Cloud Paks for Integration might eliminate the need for a customized logger application.
architecturalDecisions.motivation:
Introducing a messaging layer that would consume logging events without impacting application performance with the time consumed for logging, it’s recommended to use Kafka for that purpose.

The advantages of Kafka over MQ messaging is as follows:
• Message Persistence
• Topic partitioning
• Message sequencing
• Load balancing
• Automatic failover & High availability

alternatives.name: Event Streaming For Logging
alternatives.description: Event Streaming For Logging

alternatives.name: IBM MQ provided by IBM cloud Pak for Integration
alternatives.description: IBM MQ provided by IBM cloud Pak for Integration

architecturalDecisions.justification:
Kafka will support real time processing which is necessary for logging accuracy
The logger component requires a messaging system that has high retention and persistence also a very accurate real time processing so for that:

Kafka event streaming retains the messages even after all the subscribers have read the message and the retention period is a configurable parameter, this makes Kafka more reliable than MQ cause of message retention and state management based on the consumer offset.
architecturalDecisions.implications:
• A more reliable logging mechanism, with no impact on business applications
    • Isolating the logger component with its consumption (CPU/Memory)
    • Logging time is not consumed from message processing time

architecturalDecisions.name: Multi-Tenant Support In ODM Decision Services
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement: ODM decision services should support multi tenants
architecturalDecisions.assumptions: Many business rules are applicable for different tenants and clients
architecturalDecisions.motivation: We don’t need to start from scratch when new tenant or client ask for the same business rules.

alternatives.name: Create separate BOM projects per tenant based on the common XOM project
alternatives.description:
• Each tenant will have its own decision service
• Tenant handling logic will be the responsibility of the caller to call the decision service of this tenant

alternatives.name: Create separate XOM & BOM for each tenant
alternatives.description: Create separate XOM & BOM for each tenant
alternatives.contraindications: Too complex given that XOM is somehow generic and standard

alternatives.name: Embed the tenant handling logic in the decision service
alternatives.description: Embed the tenant handling logic in the decision service
alternatives.contraindications: Means that one decision service will serve multiple tenants – complex security handling and deployment issues

alternatives.name: Use the same BOM for all tenants
alternatives.description: Use the same BOM for all tenants
alternatives.contraindications: That will cause lookups privacy issue and availability of client specific fields in the verbalization

architecturalDecisions.decision: Create separate BOM projects per tenant based on the common XOM project
architecturalDecisions.justification:
• Client specific lookups will not be accessible by all clients when BOM is different
• No dependency for deployment of decision services in any tenant
• Simple ODM decision services governance and security

architecturalDecisions.name: Multi-Tenant Support In Object Model
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement: The object model of the product should support multi tenants
architecturalDecisions.assumptions: The product should be generic to support multi-tenants
architecturalDecisions.motivation: We don’t need to start from scratch when new tenant or client wants to use the product

alternatives.name: Create generic key value list for client specific fields and save this list along with the shipment
alternatives.description: Create generic key value list for client specific fields and save this list along with the shipment
alternatives.contraindications: ODM verbalization will not work

alternatives.name: Retrieve client specific fields before calling the ODM services that need these fields
alternatives.description:
Retrieve client specific fields before calling the ODM services that need these fields
Integration step will be added, custom code implemented everywhere
alternatives.contraindications: Integration step will be added, custom code implemented everywhere

alternatives.name: Standardize fields for all clients
alternatives.description:
Create one standardized model for the product.
Standardize fields for all clients and if client specific fields list expanded to be heavy, we can switch back to "Retrieve client specific fields" option

architecturalDecisions.justification:
• Having a standard model will make the product more efficient and serves many clients without rework
• No customized logic for each client

architecturalDecisions.name: ODM Decision Services Input
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement: ODM decision services input design
architecturalDecisions.assumptions: Business users will need to update the business rules in the future based on shipment information
architecturalDecisions.motivation: No need for IT support to update the business rules

alternatives.name: Discuss with business to add the candidate fields that might be used later and add them to the service input
alternatives.description: Discuss with business to add the candidate fields that might be used later and add them to the service input
alternatives.contraindications: business users will only be able to change rules using these fields, there will also be many wrapper classes in ODM model and many mapping services from the caller side

alternatives.name: Make the input of each service only the fields that are currently required in the business rules
alternatives.description: Make the input of each service only the fields that are currently required in the business rules
alternatives.contraindications: Business users will not be able to add new rules without referring to IT

alternatives.name: Use shipment as the main input to all ODM services
alternatives.description: Use shipment as the main input to all ODM services
alternatives.contraindications: might affect performance if shipment object becomes so huge

architecturalDecisions.decision: Use shipment as the main input to all ODM services
architecturalDecisions.justification:
• Business users will be able to change business rules freely using any shipment field
• Simplicity in ODM object model and verbalization

architecturalDecisions.name: Shipment Object Stored In Db With Only Links To Master Data
Post & Subscribe Events APIs Design
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement: Post and subscribe events APIs design in API connect
architecturalDecisions.assumptions:
All events in the system could be posted
A subset of these events could be subscribed to

alternatives.name: Create one API to post events in general and taking event name as input
alternatives.description: Create one API to post events in general and taking event name as input

alternatives.name: Create multiple APIs to subscribe to events
alternatives.description: Create multiple APIs to subscribe to events

architecturalDecisions.justification:
• To have a clear catalogue of events needed in the system noting that all of these events should be accessible for post operation
• For the subscription, it will be added complexity if we created separate APIs for each event in the product because not all of them will be part of the subscription.
• The subscription handler will be responsible of maintaining the list of events that could be subscribed to

architecturalDecisions.name: Subscription And Notifications Handlers
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement: To handle events subscriptions and notifications feature

alternatives.name: Create a separate microservice to handle subscription & notifications
alternatives.description: Create a separate microservice to handle subscription & notifications
alternatives.contraindications: Where shall we store list of events that could be subscribed to? Noting that each microservice has its own database

alternatives.name: Include subscription & notifications handling logic in the event handler microservice

Include subscription & notifications handling logic in the event handler microservice

• Notifications handler will be a new microservice
• Notification handler will call backend API to get the payload that should be sent to the external webhook
alternatives.contraindications: Events handler will be loaded by irrelevant calls to external web hooks which may affect the performance

architecturalDecisions.decision: Create a separate microservice to handle subscription & notifications
architecturalDecisions.justification:
• Notifications logic that calls external system is externalized in a separate independent microservice
• Events handler is not impacted

architecturalDecisions.name: Post Events APIs Design
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement: The client needs to have the option to post an object (shipment, consignment... etc) and event in one call.

alternatives.name: Create separate APIs in API connect, one to post event and the other to post object and event
alternatives.description: Create separate APIs in API connect, one to post event and the other to post object and event
alternatives.contraindications: Code Duplication

alternatives.name: Filing handler will handle this logic and API connect will only call one URL
alternatives.description:
• Filing handler will handle this logic and API connect will only call one URL. To simplify error handling as it became scattered between two layers leading to complexity
• Filing handler and event handler may be merged later as event handler doesn’t do anything without filing handler
alternatives.bestApplied: This alternative is simple to implement and maintain

alternatives.name: Handle this logic in APP connect
alternatives.description: Handle this logic in APP connect

alternatives.name: One API will be created for each event
alternatives.description:
• One API will be created for each event
• Payload parameter will be optional
• If payload is provided, post object then capture event (business id will be provided twice – in payload and event)
• If payload is not provided, just capture event

If payload is sent to the API, post object and then post event. Otherwise, only event will be posted.

architecturalDecisions.decision: Filing handler will handle this logic and API connect will only call one URL
architecturalDecisions.justification: Simplicity - one API for each event and the caller should decide whether he wants to send payload or not

architecturalDecisions.name: DB2 High Availability
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement:
DB2 currently is not highly available, it implements DR solution with manual failover to the DR node.
Since we host our Tenant handler and Masterdata handler components on DB2, any outage will cause the full CCS system to be unreachable.

One of the questions that needs to be answered is: do we need high availability for both tenanthandler and master data handler? or only tenant handler (since master data handler can be a recoverable)
architecturalDecisions.motivation: Keep the system up and running even after failure of DB2

alternatives.name: Find an alternative database component and keep replicating to it in the background (may be a manual replication)
alternatives.description: Find an alternative database component and keep replicating to it in the background (may be a manual replication)

alternatives.name: Keep using the DR-HA option of DB2
alternatives.description: Keep using the DR-HA option of DB2 and accept an amout of system outage according to Nike RPO & RTO requirements.

architecturalDecisions.subjectArea: Sending context data in the outbound notification events
architecturalDecisions.name: Context data to be sent in the payload of the notification events
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement: Sending context data as a separate attribute in the notification events will add complexity in dealing with payload versioning and compression

alternatives.name: Set context data object to the notification event payload
alternatives.description: Any data object that is set in the context attribute (even if received from external party) and needs to be published in the notification event must be set in the payload of the event

architecturalDecisions.decision: Set context data object to the notification event payload

architecturalDecisions.name: Implement Pub-Sub Pattern
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement:
1) Every event will have a dedicated topic where it will be published
2) Microservices will be subscribed to the event topic of interest
3) Process rules can no longer be changed without downtime so a new design has to be set to replace the process rules concept
4) A single consumer in a microservice (as the notification service) can listen to multiple event topics
5) Backlog for a single consumer to multiple topics can be eliminated by horizontal scaling
6) Each microservice can have multiple consumer groups to serve multiple purposes
7) ELK can subscriber to the event topics directly without the notification service involved? The goal is to treat ELK as an external system and receive events only from notification microservice.
8) The number of topics might explode due to the number of events
9) Events for the same purpose such as missing, retry and failed for the same feature can be emitted on the same topic
10) Implementing the pub/sub should involve a load redistribution which will result in performance boost.
11) Notification microservice will start receiving events in a more real-time approach (example: it will not depend on event handler to produce a new event, …)
architecturalDecisions.motivation: Improve the system's performance, better handling of the system resources, more control on scalability.

alternatives.name: Implement Pub-Sub
alternatives.description: Implementation of pub-sub pattern that requires the message to be produced only once and consumed by several subscribers
alternatives.bestApplied:
When fast processing is needed.
No polling is required since message topics allow instantaneous, push-based delivery.
Independent decoupling and scaling - each subscriber will determine its own scale and pace of processing messages.
alternatives.contraindications: Careful design and maintaining a stable contract is needed to avoid making the pub-sub communication error-prone.

alternatives.name: Keep Using Message Queue
alternatives.description: Current implementation is more into a Message Queue at which the publisher knows exactly the subscribers interested in a specific topic.
alternatives.bestApplied: When it is important that each message is processed (and only processed once), but it is not necessary to process messages in order.
alternatives.contraindications:
Constraints on scalability and having multiple consumers process the same message. Usually needs the message to be produced multiple times to notify all consumers.
Some topics are causing bottlenecks (to be produced and consumed) and their messages could be processed in parallel (e.g., monitoring topics)

architecturalDecisions.justification: Improve the system's performance, better handling of the system resources, more control on scalability.

architecturalDecisions.subjectArea: All application layers and load balancers
architecturalDecisions.name: Active-Active
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement: Active-Active for High availability for all application layers

alternatives.name: Region Affinity - Approach 3 - using CIS
alternatives.description: Diagram to be added
alternatives.bestApplied: - Disaster situation: LB to switch to the other region  without restarting Filing Handler
alternatives.contraindications:
- two CIS LBs instead of one.. two integration points (one for each region)
- BE configuration will point to two endpoints
- APP Connect configuration impacted needs separate endpoints for FRK and LON

alternatives.name: Region affinity - Approach 1 - using single endpoint
alternatives.description:
CCS flow starting point is from API Connect calls. Whether the call is triggered from Integration layer or Front end, we need to make sure that once the BE receives the call in a certain region --> the whole flow should continue in the same region.

Approach:
- One single domain CIS
- two citrix LB - one in FRK and one in LON
- When CIS receives the request, it should route the request to either Citrix FRK or Citrix LON based on the caller region
- Citrix FRK will send the calls to ODM FRK and Citrix LON will send the calls to ODM LON
alternatives.bestApplied:
- One endpoint without separating endpoints for different regions
- No network latency as all calls will be on the same region
alternatives.contraindications:
- Difficulty in implementation. When CIS receives the request, it doesn't know the region of the caller. A ticket will be created with IBM Cloud support to investigate further. Could be through edge functions, or checking header parameters that are pre-calculated by cloudflare CIS
- Citrix is not needed. We could have only CIB that routes the requests to ODM FRK or LON. However, due to cloudflare issues than occur when CIS is configured to call different ODM domains --> Citrix is required as a workaround. If cloudflare issue is resolved --> Citrix could be removed from this

alternatives.name: Region affinity - Approach 2 - two endpoints using citrix
alternatives.description:
CCS flow starting point is from API Connect calls. Whether the call is triggered from Integration layer or Front end, we need to make sure that once the BE receives the call in a certain region --> the whole flow should continue in the same region.
Approach:
- Two layers depending on CIS (acting as DNS and protection layer). CIS above citrix
- FRK rill route to FRK, LON route to LON
alternatives.bestApplied:
- Request will continue in the same region - no latency
- Straight forward implementation
alternatives.contraindications:
- separate endpoints that will need to be handled in the configuration of backend, interation
- Two endpoints for APIs shared with NIKE?

alternatives.name: Switch round robin between the two ODM subscriptions
alternatives.description: Switch round robin between the two ODM subscriptions. Same applies for other CCS components
alternatives.bestApplied: 1. Easy and straight forward implementation
alternatives.contraindications:
1. Latency between regions FRK & LON
History: Last year black week tests results showed that there is network latency when the calls are triggered from FRK to ODM London. Based on this decision, we decided to depend mainly on the same region and keep the other region as backup.

architecturalDecisions.decision: Region affinity - Approach 1 - using single endpoint
architecturalDecisions.justification:
• If the flow started in FRK, it should continue in FRK. Same applies for LON

Notes:
1. CIS can't work on two regions at the same time due to the issues of CIS - different domain without changing page rule.
Citrix doesn't have this issue and can route to different regions at the same time
2. How to know the region to direct the call to the region.. not supported by GLB.. it must support routing policy but will not work with CIS

architecturalDecisions.name: API Connect upgrade - gateway selection
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement:
CCS is currently built using API Connect Sas version 5. This version is sunset and expected end of support date to be end of 2022.
It is required to upgrade API Connect version to version 10.
There are two types of upgrades:
1. Simple upgrade
2. Advanced upgrade

alternatives.name: Advanced upgrade
alternatives.description:
Advanced upgrade is to upgrade the APIs from version 5 to version 10 including the gateway (called native gateway)
Migration is not as simple as simple upgrade from implementation point of view. However, this is the latest gateway version and the performance will be significantly enhanced 5x-15x the current performance of version 5
alternatives.bestApplied: Performance is significant factor here.

alternatives.name: Simple upgrade
alternatives.description:
Simple upgrade is easier in implementation.
Simple upgrade keeps using the same gateway version used by API Connect version 5.
alternatives.bestApplied: When easy and fast upgrade is needed
alternatives.contraindications:
By simple upgrade:
performance will only be enhanced by 15%
later on, we will need to upgrade to the latest version of gateway

architecturalDecisions.justification:
Advanced upgrade is the selected approach because the upgrade will be done to the latest version and also we will benefit from the performance enhancement 5-10 times the current performance of version 5.
It is ok to spend more time to upgrade the APIs one time to the latest and more performing version.
Also most of the APIs are implemented using the same structure so same upgrade steps will be done for all APIs.

architecturalDecisions.name: APIC Upgrade process
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement:
CCS APIs are currently implemented on API Connect Sas version 5 which is sunset in April and expected end of support date is end of 2022.
There are two ways to perform the APIs upgrade:
  1. API Connect migration utility
  2. Manual upgrade

alternatives.name: API Connect migration utility
alternatives.description:
There is a utility that does the upgrade from version 5 to version 10.
Since in AD-020 Advanced upgrade is selected --> upgrade utility will need some manual effort to make the APIs compatible with version 10.

alternatives.name: Manual uprade
alternatives.description: This approach is to manual update CCS APIs to the latest version without using any migration utility.

architecturalDecisions.justification:
• It is risky to use upgrade utility specially that we will need to perform manual changes in all cases to support the advanced upgrade
  • All APIs are following the same pattern of implementation so it will not be very complicated to manual update them
  • Once the team is familiar with the new syntax and components of version 10, we can start implementing the APIs using the latest version and test the results

architecturalDecisions.topic: Selection of an alternative for API-Connect.
architecturalDecisions.name: API Connect upgrade environment selection
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement:
CCS APIs are currently implemented on API Connect SasS version 5 which is expected to sunset by end of Jul 2023. The cloud team informed of few options that we can choose from going forward.

There are three options to host APIs using version 10:
  1. Cloudpak for integration: on openshift anywhere
  2. IBM API Connect: Deployable on-prem or any cloud, bring your own openshift or K8 or Ovas on VMware
  3. IBM Cloud: Reserved instance is a managed single tenant instance with ability to add on-prem gateways
Assessment is needed to compare the three approaches from different perspectives such as cost, maintainability, management, DR and support
architecturalDecisions.assumptions: Cloud Pak for Integration is already used in the solution to utilize App-Connect.
architecturalDecisions.motivation: Achieve best performance and control with minimum cloud and services cost.

alternatives.name: AWS API-Connect SaaS
alternatives.description:
A shared API-Connect SaaS model is provided on AWS.

References: https://aws.amazon.com/marketplace/pp/prodview-b3u5z3pv4wccg
alternatives.bestApplied: • Management: Operation support will be the responsibility of the AWS Team.
alternatives.contraindications:
• Cost: $9000 for 50M API calls with a commitment for 12 months.
  • Performance: Slower performance due to hosting on two different cloud providers.
  • Network Traffic: Network delays and network cost will be expected since the rest of the Environment is hosted on IBM Cloud while the API-C will be hosted on AWS.
  • Management: the operation team has to deal with two different management layers.
  • Monitoring: Separate monitoring will be needed and also need to be correlated with the rest of the environment hosted on IBM Cloud.
  • DevOps Integration: Will require two different set of DevOps management. One for AWS API-C services and another one for IBM Cloud Services.

alternatives.name: Use API-Connect as part of the Cloud Pack for Integration
alternatives.description: Leverage the current usage of the Cloud Pak for Integration (CP4I) to serve API-Connect as well as App-Connect functionalities.
alternatives.bestApplied:
• Utilize existing knowledge and support of the CP4I
  • Monitoring: Will utilize the monitoring system used for the other components hosted on the IBM Cloud (e.g. New Relic)
  • Network Traffic: Utilizing the IBM Cloud internal free traffic between the components.
  • DevOps Integration: Will use the IBM Cloud Pipelines
alternatives.contraindications:
• Cost: Requires extra licenses for API-Connect by extending the current licenses used for App-Connect as part of the CP4I.
  • Performance: More control over performance since the infrastructure is managed by the team.
  • Management: Extra operation effort will be expected from the support team to support the new API-Connect on CP4I

alternatives.name: Use a Cloud Dedicated API-Connect Instance
alternatives.description: A new service for API-Connect using a dedicated instance will be provided by the IBM cloud. This dedicated instance will be managed by the IBM cloud team.
alternatives.bestApplied:
• Operation support will be the responsibility of the IBM Cloud Team.
  • Network Traffic: Utilizing the IBM Cloud internal free traffic between the components.
  • Management: Management will be done by the SaaS provider team.
  • Monitoring: Will be monitored a service response time only since it is a SaaS service.
  • DevOps Integration: Will use the IBM Cloud Pipelines
alternatives.contraindications:
• Cost: Dedicated Instance is usually higher cost than a shared SaaS or self operated models.
  • Performance: Performance could be impacted by noisy neighbors since it is a SaaS service.

architecturalDecisions.decision: Use API-Connect as part of the Cloud Pack for Integration
architecturalDecisions.justification: Minimize the cost and leverage the existing Cloud Pak for Integration installation and support.
architecturalDecisions.implications: Extra effort and license will be required.

architecturalDecisions.topic: Scaling up/down for IKS and Event Streams
architecturalDecisions.name: Event Streams & IKS Elasticity
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement: Select an Approach for the Scaling up/down for IKS and Event Streams
architecturalDecisions.motivation: Able to scale up and down the services based on the expected traffic workload.

alternatives.name: Upscale using a new IKS cluster with a new Event Streams Instance
alternatives.description:
In this option the following steps will be used for scaling up:
  1. A new instance of Event Streams will be created
  2. A new IKS cluster hosting the micro-services will be created with its worker pool and its set of worker nodes
  3. A new set of micro-services will be created and will be pointing to the new event streams instance.
  4. The traffic will be directed to the old and new micro-services
In this option the following steps will be used for scaling down:
  1. The traffic will not be directed to the new micro-services.
  2. The new micro-services will be removed by deleting the new IKS cluster with its worker pool and its worker nodes.
  3. The new instance of Event Streams will be deleted
alternatives.bestApplied:
• Easy to downscale after all the traffic is stopped from IKS.
  • Flexibility of the location of the upscaled components in different regions or different zones or even the same zone.
alternatives.contraindications:
• Treating the IKS and its associated event streams as one unit of upscaling or downscaling.
  • Granularity of up/downscaling is in steps (not smooth) for both IKS and Event Streams

alternatives.name: Upscaling by extending the IKS cluster and extending the Event Streams Instance
alternatives.description:
In this option the following steps will be used for scaling up:
  1. The capacity of the existing Event Streams will be increased.
  2. The existing IKS cluster hosting the micro-services will be extended by adding a new worker pool with its set of worker nodes to the same IKS cluster.
  3. A new set of micro-services will be created and will be pointing to the existing event streams instance.
  4. The traffic will be directed to the old and new micro-services
In this option the following steps will be used for scaling down:
  1. The traffic will not be directed to the new micro-services.
  2. The new micro-services will be removed by deleting the new worker pool and its worker nodes
  3. However, there is no way figured out yet for scaling down the event streams.

Conclusion: This option is not fully workable due to there is no clear way for scaling down the event stream instance.
alternatives.bestApplied: • Utilizing the existing IKS and Event Streams instances.
alternatives.contraindications: • There is no way figured out yet for scaling down the event streams.

alternatives.name: Upscaling by extending the IKS cluster with a new Event Streams Instance
alternatives.description:
In this option the following steps will be used for scaling up:
  1. A new instance of Event Streams will be created
  2. The existing IKS cluster hosting the micro-services will be extended by adding a new worker pool with its set of worker nodes to the same IKS cluster
  3. A new set of micro-services will be created and will be pointing to the new event streams instance.
  4. The traffic will be directed to the old and new micro-services
In this option the following steps will be used for scaling down:
  1. The traffic will not be directed to the new micro-services.
  2. The new micro-services will be removed by deleting the new worker pool and its worker nodes
  3. The new instance of Event Streams will be deleted
alternatives.bestApplied:
• Easy to downscale after all the traffic is stopped from IKS.
  • Utilizing the same IKS cluster overhead
alternatives.contraindications:
• Upscaling can be done in the same region only.
  • Granularity of up/downscaling is in steps (not smooth) for the Event Streams.

architecturalDecisions.name: ODM multi-tenancy
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement:
Based on the assessment of new tenants that are onboarded to Customs Compliance Platform, there are two options:
1. Reuse one IBM ODM on Cloud subscription to serve multiple tenants
2. Have separate IBM ODM on Cloud subscriptions for each tenant
This Architectural Decision focuses on option 1 and the alternatives of this approach
architecturalDecisions.assumptions: Assessment is done for the tenants that will be onboarded and will share the same IBM ODM on Cloud subscription. This assessment should cover several aspects such as: the shared infrastructure, expected loads...etc.
architecturalDecisions.motivation:
1. Reusing available existing resources that still have the capacity to handle extra loads for other tenants
2. Cost

alternatives.name: Create new internal adaptor to act as tenants orchestrator
alternatives.description:
A new component will be created to handle the ODM calls through pub/sub as a part of the current event-driven architecture.
  1. The feature will post event on Kafka
  2. The adaptor will subscribe to the event and call the corresponding ODM service
  3. ODM adaptor will parse the ODM response and post another event on Kafka for the next feature to be triggered
  4. Failures must be handled through events
alternatives.bestApplied:
1. Decoupling of ODM.
  2. Including ODM to CCP event-driven architecture is more flexible an dynamic.
  3. Extensible solution
  4. The current approach of direct calls from the microservices and integration layers is coupling all layers together
alternatives.contraindications: Effort needed to refactor of all backend and integration features calling ODM is needed to use the new adaptor for orchestration

alternatives.name: Event-driven using Business Automation Insights
alternatives.description: Introduce Business Automation Insights to include ODM in CCP event-driven architecture. ODM will be executing the required decision services based on the posted events.
alternatives.bestApplied:
1. Decoupling of ODM.
  2. Including ODM to CCP event-driven architecture is more flexible an dynamic.
  3. Extensible solution
  4. The current approach of direct calls from the microservices and integration layers is coupling all layers together
alternatives.contraindications: This will require to move from IBM ODM on Cloud Saas to CP4A

alternatives.name: Introducing routing DB2 table
alternatives.description: Introducing new DB2 table including tenant configurations. This table should support the consumers to retrieve the corresponding ODM endpoint for each feature and for each tenant.
alternatives.bestApplied: Simple implementation
alternatives.contraindications:
1. Increased DB calls to retrieve flow configuration
  2. Having too many configured features and endpoints will make it difficult to be maintained
  3. Possibility of errors

alternatives.name: ODM acting as tenants orchestrator
alternatives.description:
ODM will be responsible for orchestrating the calls to the target tenant.
  1. Consumer will send a value representing the current tenant to the ODM decision services
  2. ODM service will execute the rules of the input tenant
  3. ODM will respond to the consumer with the response
alternatives.bestApplied: Simplified Backend changes. The only needed change is to pass the tenant as a parameter to all ODM decision services.
alternatives.contraindications:
1. Very high complexity at ODM side to orchestrate and maintain all tenants flows in one ODM call
  2. ODM is a business rules management system and should not be misused as orchestration

architecturalDecisions.justification:
• Decoupling of applications layer. Each layer will be responsible for a clear objective:
  1. ODM: Only business rules execution
  2. Orchestrator adaptor: Orchestrate ODM calls
  3. Micro services and integration: Execution of their main logic
  • Extensible solution.
  • Expanding Event-driven approach across all application layers
  • Fault tolerance and Enhanced performance through kafka

architecturalDecisions.name: Event Streams & IKS Micro Services Elasticity
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement: Need to address how the elasticity to scale up and scale down the event streams and Kubernetes environments that host the micro services will be addressed.
architecturalDecisions.assumptions: The micro services hosted on Kubernetes cluster need to be tied to specific event streams end point. If the end point changes the service pods need to be restarted.
architecturalDecisions.motivation:
Scaling up and scaling down are currently manual process and need to be automated. There is a need to scale up the environment in several cases such as:
* High traffic happen in the system
* In preparation of anticipated high work loads (e.g. Black week or Promotions).
* In case of moving the traffic to a lower capacity environment (e.g. Standby environment with partial capacity)

Also the solution need to take into consideration the feasibility of scaling down again after there is no more need of the higher capacity environment.

alternatives.name: Scale Event Streams in a new Cluster and the IKS hosted Micro Services in a new Cluster
alternatives.description:
In this alternative, the Event Streams upscaling will create its own event streams cluster. Also the Micro services will be scaled up by creating a new Kubernetes cluster. These newly created micro services will be pointing to the newly created events streams. Accordingly there will be groups of micro services cluster coupled with their event streams cluster.
  1. Create and configure a new Event Streams cluster
  2. Create and configure a new Kubernetes cluster.
  3. Create a new set of micro services on the Kubernetes cluster that point to the newly created event streams
Configure the load balancer to utilize the new Kubernetes cluster.

In case of downscaling, the traffic coming to the micro services will be stopped. Accordingly after a while, all the events in the event stream cluster will be consumed. At this stage downscaling can be completed by decommissioning both the event streams cluster and the Kubernetes cluster that host the micro services.
  1. Stop the traffic to the newly created set of micro services by removing them from the load balancer.
  2. Wait till all the events in the associated even streams cluster are consumed.
  3. Delete the newly created Kubernetes cluster.
  4. Delete the newly created event streams cluster.
alternatives.bestApplied:
• Downscaling will be simpler than other approaches.
  • This process can be repeated multiple times to get new clusters.
  • The upscaling can be done in another data center.
  • Better control over the capacity to be added for each cluster
alternatives.contraindications:
• Scaling up and down will be step wise according to the cluster granularity.
  • Have overhead for a new IKS cluster (Master nodes, ... etc.)

alternatives.name: Scale Event Streams in a new Cluster and the IKS hosted Micro Services in a the same Cluster
alternatives.description:
In this alternative, a new event streams cluster will be created. Also The existing Kubernetes cluster will be scaled horizontally by adding new worker nodes. After add the new worker nodes, a new set of the micro services will be created to point to the new event streams.

  1. Create and configure a new Event Streams cluster
  2. Add worker nodes to the Kubernetes cluster
  3. Create a new set of micro services on the Kubernetes cluster that point to the newly created event streams
  4. Add the new micro services to the load balancer

Downscaling will be achieved by stopping the traffic to the newly created micro services and when the associated events it their associated event stream cluster are consumed the process for downscaling will be completed by decommissioning the newly created event streams and then deleting the pods of the micro service that are using these event streams. At the end we can delete the worker nodes.
  1. Stop the traffic to the newly created set of micro services by removing them from the load balancer.
  2. Wait till all the events in the associated even streams cluster are consumed.
  3. Delete the newly created micro services
  4. Delete the newly created event streams cluster
  5. Delete the worker nodes from the Kubernetes cluster.
alternatives.bestApplied: • Utilize the existing IKS cluster by using the same cluster management nodes
alternatives.contraindications:
• Splitting the traffic between the old and the new micro services could be challenging.
  • Can not be scaled up using another data center/region.

alternatives.name: Scale Event Streams independent of Kubernetes hosted Micro Services Using Existing Clusters
alternatives.description:
This alternative relies on the existing Kubernetes and Event Stream Clusters to scale up the environment


Up Scaling Steps
  1. Scale up the event streams cluster by requesting additional capacity and additional storage
  2. Create a new set of Worker nodes/Worker pool in the Kubernetes cluster
  3. Create a new set of the IKS micro services by increasing the number of Pods of the existing services


Down Scaling steps:
  1. Create a new scaled down Event Streams cluster with a lower capacity
  2. Create a new set of Worker nodes/Worker pool in the Kubernetes cluster
  3. Create a new set of the IKS micro services to point to the new scaled down Event Streams cluster
  4. Stop the traffic to the old micro services
  5. Wait till all the events in the high spec Event Streams cluster is consumed
  6. Delete the old micro services that use the high spec Event Streams cluster
  7. Delete the high spec Event Streams cluster
  8. Scale the number of worker nodes in the Kubernetes cluster
alternatives.bestApplied: • Fast scaling in the same infrastructure
alternatives.contraindications:
• Scaling down is challenging
  • Can not be scaled up using another data center/region

architecturalDecisions.decision: Scale Event Streams in a new Cluster and the IKS hosted Micro Services in a the same Cluster
architecturalDecisions.justification: It will be feasible to scale down after there is no need to keep the scaled up event streams and IKS micro services.
architecturalDecisions.implications: Need to develop and test the scripts for upscaling and downscaling of both the Event Streams and the Kubernetes hosting the micro services.

architecturalDecisions.name: Cloud Foundry Alternative For CCP Frontend
architecturalDecisions.problemStatement:
IBM Cloud Foundry Service is planned to be sunset by June 1, 2023. Another service or component is needed to host CCP Frontend web application.

There are three options available to host CCP Web Application:
  1. IBM Cloud Code Engine
  2. IBM Cloud Kubernetes Service
  3. Red Hat OpenShift on IBM Cloud
An assessment is required to compare the different alternatives from different aspects such as elasticity, cost, maintainability

alternatives.name: IBM Cloud Code Engine
alternatives.description:
IBM Cloud Code Engine is a fully managed, serverless platform that runs your containerized workloads

Ref. https://cloud.ibm.com/docs/codeengine
alternatives.bestApplied:
Elasticity: Auto-scaling based on number of HTTP requests is built in (Minimum instances are down to zero and max instances are up to 250 instance)
Cost: Only pay for when workloads run (GB-sec, vCPU-sec & invocations)
Management: Managed Application. No container, cluster, networking, or infrastructure skills required
Monitoring: Will be monitored using New Relic
DevOps: Integrated with IBM Cloud Pipelines

alternatives.name: IBM Cloud Kubernetes Service
alternatives.description:
IBM Kubernetes container orchestration platform.

Ref. https://cloud.ibm.com/docs/containers
alternatives.bestApplied:
Elasticity: Auto-scaling based on number of HTTP requests is built in.
Management: Managed Cluster
Monitoring: Will be monitored using New Relic
DevOps: Integrated with IBM Cloud Pipelines
alternatives.contraindications: Cost: Cluster (size of cluster * time) + integrations (GB-time) + load balancers (cost * time)

alternatives.name: Red Hat OpenShift on IBM Cloud
alternatives.description:
A managed Red Hat OpenShift cloud service that reduces operational complexity and helps organizations build and scale applications with the security of IBM Cloud

https://www.ibm.com/eg-en/cloud/openshift
alternatives.bestApplied:
Elasticity: On Red Hat OpenShift on IBM Cloud, applications are synonymous to pods. With Kubernetes, you can automatically scale up or down your pods based on CPU or memory
Management: Managed Cluster
Monitoring: Will be monitored using New Relic
DevOps: Integrated with IBM Cloud Pipelines
alternatives.contraindications: Cost: OCP license + Cluster (size of cluster * time) + integrations (GB-time) + load balancers (cost * time) Can obtain an OCP license if you get Cloud Paks

risks.name: R-001 Reusing ODM subscription for multi-tenants
risks.description:
Assessment must be done when new tenants are onboarded to the Customs Compliance Platform. The outcome of this assessment could be that one ODM on Cloud subscription will be used by multiple tenants.
This decision raises the following risks that must be considered:
1. Tenants will share the same ODM on Cloud infrastructure. This means that in case of increased load of any of the tenants, other tenants could be impacted. Note: ODM on Cloud doesn't have auto-scaling capabilities
2. Increased load during black week for all tenants could impact the performance
risks.recommendation:
1. Detailed analysis for tenants loads and volumes must be done before taking the decision of sharing one ODM subscription
2. This decision must be revisited before black week or any period with expected high load

properties.problemStatement: Select an Approach for the Scaling up/down for IKS and Event Streams
properties.motivation: Able to scale up and down the services based on the expected traffic workload.
properties.name: Event Streams & IKS Elasticity
properties.topic: Scaling up/down for IKS and Event Streams

properties.implications: Extra effort and license will be required.
properties.problemStatement:
CCS APIs are currently implemented on API Connect SasS version 5 which is expected to sunset by end of Jul 2023. The cloud team informed of few options that we can choose from going forward.

There are three options to host APIs using version 10:
  1. Cloudpak for integration: on openshift anywhere
  2. IBM API Connect: Deployable on-prem or any cloud, bring your own openshift or K8 or Ovas on VMware
  3. IBM Cloud: Reserved instance is a managed single tenant instance with ability to add on-prem gateways
Assessment is needed to compare the three approaches from different perspectives such as cost, maintainability, management, DR and support
properties.motivation: Achieve best performance and control with minimum cloud and services cost.
properties.assumptions: Cloud Pak for Integration is already used in the solution to utilize App-Connect.
properties.name: API Connect upgrade environment selection
properties.topic: Selection of an alternative for API-Connect.
properties.justification: Minimize the cost and leverage the existing Cloud Pak for Integration installation and support.

properties.implications:
• Enhancing the performance 
    • Solidifying and securing the integration data layer
    • Giving the tenant all the rights needed to control/manage App Connect database
properties.problemStatement:
Either using a dedicated or shared Cloudant instance for App Connect

• Read/Write operations and global queries' quota limitation for the shared database instance between backend and App Connect
• Delays resulted from waiting for R/W operations might impact App connect performance
• A shared database would be a single point of failure for both integration and the core layer in case of outage
properties.motivation:
• Solidify the integration data layer with a tenant-isolated database
• Increase overall security as the App Connect layer is controlled by tenant
• Support different availability requirements and simplify administration and backup for different backup schedules and recovery models
properties.derivedRequirements: DevOps requirements for the backup and recovery of the new database instance
properties.name: App Connect Data Layer Addition (Cloudant + COS)
properties.subjectArea: Provision a dedicated Cloudant instance for App Connect usage

properties.problemStatement: Active-Active for High availability for all application layers
properties.name: Active-Active
properties.subjectArea: All application layers and load balancers
properties.justification:
• If the flow started in FRK, it should continue in FRK. Same applies for LON

Notes:
1. CIS can't work on two regions at the same time due to the issues of CIS - different domain without changing page rule.
Citrix doesn't have this issue and can route to different regions at the same time
2. How to know the region to direct the call to the region.. not supported by GLB.. it must support routing policy but will not work with CIS

properties.name: Shipment Object Stored In Db With Only Links To Master Data

properties.problemStatement: Due to budget, the decision of using APP connect is revisited to find other alternatives
properties.name: App Connect Alternatives

properties.implications:
• A more reliable logging mechanism, with no impact on business applications
    • Isolating the logger component with its consumption (CPU/Memory)
    • Logging time is not consumed from message processing time
properties.problemStatement:
• The current logging service (LogDNA) truncates large payload, so a customized logger application is developed to store payloads in cloud object storage while using LogDNA Ingest API to log COS URLs
• LogDNA Ingest API is having a performance impact on application performance because of the consumed time for logging
properties.motivation:
Introducing a messaging layer that would consume logging events without impacting application performance with the time consumed for logging, it’s recommended to use Kafka for that purpose.

The advantages of Kafka over MQ messaging is as follows:
• Message Persistence
• Topic partitioning
• Message sequencing
• Load balancing
• Automatic failover & High availability
properties.assumptions: Usage of common services for logging and monitoring provided by IBM Cloud Paks for Integration might eliminate the need for a customized logger application.
properties.name: App Connect Kafka vs. MQ Support For Logging Optimization (Kafka Standard) - Compare With MQ In The Cloud Pak
properties.subjectArea: Event streaming vs. Messaging for App connect logger
properties.justification:
Kafka will support real time processing which is necessary for logging accuracy
The logger component requires a messaging system that has high retention and persistence also a very accurate real time processing so for that:

Kafka event streaming retains the messages even after all the subscribers have read the message and the retention period is a configurable parameter, this makes Kafka more reliable than MQ cause of message retention and state management based on the consumer offset.

properties.problemStatement: Post and subscribe events APIs design in API connect
properties.assumptions:
All events in the system could be posted
A subset of these events could be subscribed to
properties.name: Post & Subscribe Events APIs Design
properties.justification:
• To have a clear catalogue of events needed in the system noting that all of these events should be accessible for post operation
• For the subscription, it will be added complexity if we created separate APIs for each event in the product because not all of them will be part of the subscription.
• The subscription handler will be responsible of maintaining the list of events that could be subscribed to

properties.problemStatement: Sending context data as a separate attribute in the notification events will add complexity in dealing with payload versioning and compression
properties.name: Context data to be sent in the payload of the notification events
properties.subjectArea: Sending context data in the outbound notification events

properties.implications:
• Increase agility and productivity
    • Fully support the agile integration architecture concepts.
    • Dynamic scalability and inherit resilience
    • Management and maintainability provided with OpenShift CP4I
properties.problemStatement:
As currently designed, using ACE SaaS offering on IBM cloud; we’ve experienced the following issues:
• Lack of monitoring for container’s consumption (CPU/Memory)
• Automated deployment is not supported in ACE SaaS offering, only manual deployments through the dashboard
• Occurrence of multiple unplanned outage incidents with ACE SaaS
• There are no supported management APIs to manage the running servers and perform health checks
• Container logs are not meeting technical requirements for logging necessary business data in order to support in troubleshooting integration flows
properties.motivation:
• Considering the aggressive workload and expected throughput for Brexit, the current ACE SaaS architecture wouldn’t support HA and auto-scalability
• More reliable deployments with Red Hat OpenShift and utilization of docker and container orchestration capabilities
• Automated deployments for integration flows and eliminate the risk caused by manual interference
properties.relatedDecisions:
• RH OpenShift container platform to deploy cloud pack for integration
    • Non-production environment to only have different entitlement and HA won’t be supported for cost saving
properties.name: App Connect Deployment Strategy
properties.subjectArea: Using Cloud Pack For Integration Along With OpenShift Container Platform vs App Connect SaaS Offering
properties.justification:
• Fine-grained deployment and pipeline automated deployments are supported through OpenShift container platform
• IBM Cloud Paks for integration provides logging service (based on the ELK stack) and monitoring service (based on Prometheus and Grafana)
• Monitoring for integration servers’ consumption would alert if any expected failures and action can be taken to increase scalability

properties.problemStatement: ODM decision services should support multi tenants
properties.motivation: We don’t need to start from scratch when new tenant or client ask for the same business rules.
properties.assumptions: Many business rules are applicable for different tenants and clients
properties.name: Multi-Tenant Support In ODM Decision Services
properties.justification:
• Client specific lookups will not be accessible by all clients when BOM is different
• No dependency for deployment of decision services in any tenant
• Simple ODM decision services governance and security

properties.implications: Need to develop and test the scripts for upscaling and downscaling of both the Event Streams and the Kubernetes hosting the micro services.
properties.problemStatement: Need to address how the elasticity to scale up and scale down the event streams and Kubernetes environments that host the micro services will be addressed.
properties.motivation:
Scaling up and scaling down are currently manual process and need to be automated. There is a need to scale up the environment in several cases such as:
* High traffic happen in the system
* In preparation of anticipated high work loads (e.g. Black week or Promotions).
* In case of moving the traffic to a lower capacity environment (e.g. Standby environment with partial capacity)

Also the solution need to take into consideration the feasibility of scaling down again after there is no more need of the higher capacity environment.
properties.assumptions: The micro services hosted on Kubernetes cluster need to be tied to specific event streams end point. If the end point changes the service pods need to be restarted.
properties.name: Event Streams & IKS Micro Services Elasticity
properties.justification: It will be feasible to scale down after there is no need to keep the scaled up event streams and IKS micro services.

properties.problemStatement:
Based on the assessment of new tenants that are onboarded to Customs Compliance Platform, there are two options:
1. Reuse one IBM ODM on Cloud subscription to serve multiple tenants
2. Have separate IBM ODM on Cloud subscriptions for each tenant
This Architectural Decision focuses on option 1 and the alternatives of this approach
properties.motivation:
1. Reusing available existing resources that still have the capacity to handle extra loads for other tenants
2. Cost
properties.assumptions: Assessment is done for the tenants that will be onboarded and will share the same IBM ODM on Cloud subscription. This assessment should cover several aspects such as: the shared infrastructure, expected loads...etc.
properties.name: ODM multi-tenancy
properties.justification:
• Decoupling of applications layer. Each layer will be responsible for a clear objective:
  1. ODM: Only business rules execution
  2. Orchestrator adaptor: Orchestrate ODM calls
  3. Micro services and integration: Execution of their main logic
  • Extensible solution.
  • Expanding Event-driven approach across all application layers
  • Fault tolerance and Enhanced performance through kafka

properties.problemStatement:
DB2 currently is not highly available, it implements DR solution with manual failover to the DR node.
Since we host our Tenant handler and Masterdata handler components on DB2, any outage will cause the full CCS system to be unreachable.

One of the questions that needs to be answered is: do we need high availability for both tenanthandler and master data handler? or only tenant handler (since master data handler can be a recoverable)
properties.motivation: Keep the system up and running even after failure of DB2
properties.name: DB2 High Availability

properties.problemStatement: To handle events subscriptions and notifications feature
properties.name: Subscription And Notifications Handlers
properties.justification:
• Notifications logic that calls external system is externalized in a separate independent microservice
• Events handler is not impacted

properties.problemStatement: The client needs to have the option to post an object (shipment, consignment... etc) and event in one call.
properties.name: Post Events APIs Design
properties.justification: Simplicity - one API for each event and the caller should decide whether he wants to send payload or not

properties.problemStatement:
1) Every event will have a dedicated topic where it will be published
2) Microservices will be subscribed to the event topic of interest
3) Process rules can no longer be changed without downtime so a new design has to be set to replace the process rules concept
4) A single consumer in a microservice (as the notification service) can listen to multiple event topics
5) Backlog for a single consumer to multiple topics can be eliminated by horizontal scaling
6) Each microservice can have multiple consumer groups to serve multiple purposes
7) ELK can subscriber to the event topics directly without the notification service involved? The goal is to treat ELK as an external system and receive events only from notification microservice.
8) The number of topics might explode due to the number of events
9) Events for the same purpose such as missing, retry and failed for the same feature can be emitted on the same topic
10) Implementing the pub/sub should involve a load redistribution which will result in performance boost.
11) Notification microservice will start receiving events in a more real-time approach (example: it will not depend on event handler to produce a new event, …)
properties.motivation: Improve the system's performance, better handling of the system resources, more control on scalability.
properties.name: Implement Pub-Sub Pattern
properties.justification: Improve the system's performance, better handling of the system resources, more control on scalability.

properties.problemStatement:
CCS is currently built using API Connect Sas version 5. This version is sunset and expected end of support date to be end of 2022.
It is required to upgrade API Connect version to version 10.
There are two types of upgrades:
1. Simple upgrade
2. Advanced upgrade
properties.name: API Connect upgrade - gateway selection
properties.justification:
Advanced upgrade is the selected approach because the upgrade will be done to the latest version and also we will benefit from the performance enhancement 5-10 times the current performance of version 5.
It is ok to spend more time to upgrade the APIs one time to the latest and more performing version.
Also most of the APIs are implemented using the same structure so same upgrade steps will be done for all APIs.

properties.problemStatement: The object model of the product should support multi tenants
properties.motivation: We don’t need to start from scratch when new tenant or client wants to use the product
properties.assumptions: The product should be generic to support multi-tenants
properties.name: Multi-Tenant Support In Object Model
properties.justification:
• Having a standard model will make the product more efficient and serves many clients without rework
• No customized logic for each client

properties.problemStatement: ODM decision services input design
properties.motivation: No need for IT support to update the business rules
properties.assumptions: Business users will need to update the business rules in the future based on shipment information
properties.name: ODM Decision Services Input
properties.justification:
• Business users will be able to change business rules freely using any shipment field
• Simplicity in ODM object model and verbalization

properties.problemStatement:
IBM Cloud Foundry Service is planned to be sunset by June 1, 2023. Another service or component is needed to host CCP Frontend web application.

There are three options available to host CCP Web Application:
  1. IBM Cloud Code Engine
  2. IBM Cloud Kubernetes Service
  3. Red Hat OpenShift on IBM Cloud
An assessment is required to compare the different alternatives from different aspects such as elasticity, cost, maintainability
properties.name: Cloud Foundry Alternative For CCP Frontend

properties.problemStatement:
CCS APIs are currently implemented on API Connect Sas version 5 which is sunset in April and expected end of support date is end of 2022.
There are two ways to perform the APIs upgrade:
  1. API Connect migration utility
  2. Manual upgrade
properties.name: APIC Upgrade process
properties.justification:
• It is risky to use upgrade utility specially that we will need to perform manual changes in all cases to support the advanced upgrade
  • All APIs are following the same pattern of implementation so it will not be very complicated to manual update them
  • Once the team is familiar with the new syntax and components of version 10, we can start implementing the APIs using the latest version and test the results
